      },
      {
        "type": "callout",
        "calloutEmoji": "üëâ",
        "calloutText": "<strong>Help us grow </strong>by following us on social media:<br>‚Ä¢ <a href=\"https://www.twitter.com/LeverNews\">Twitter</a><br>‚Ä¢ <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/TheLeverNews\">Facebook</a><br>‚Ä¢ <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/LeverNews\">Instagram</a><br>‚Ä¢ <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/c/LeverNews\">YouTube</a>",
        "backgroundColor": "blue"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The key element that could help address the problem is the pay-to-play rule‚Äôs ‚Äúanti-circumvention‚Äù provision, which states that the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) ‚Äúprohibits acts done indirectly, which, if done directly, would violate the rule.‚Äù This little-noticed provision means that if you are trying to bypass a campaign contribution ban by making a donation to an independent political action committee, that‚Äôs not allowed either.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "But in the rule‚Äôs twelve-year history, the anti-circumvention provision has never ‚Äî that‚Äôs right, ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "never ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "‚Äî been enforced.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The provision continues to collect dust despite the enormous expansion of super PACs, which allow unlimited contributions and spending while officially not coordinating with campaigns.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "In the case of DeSantis, direct contributions from private equity executives to the Florida governor likely would have triggered alarm bells at the SEC, especially as those same private equity firms nabbed millions in state pension dollars. Instead, these Wall Street interests donated to a 527 group ‚Äî similar to SuperPACs, but allows direct contributions to state campaigns ‚Äî called the Republican Governors Association, which in turn donated to ‚ÄúFriends of Ron DeSantis,‚Äù a non-official committee that coordinated directly with the governor on campaign matters. So far, the SEC hasn‚Äôt done anything to signal that this arrangement could run afoul of the anti-circumvention provision.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "And this is just one example. In 2022, private equity ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "spent",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://www.wsj.com/articles/private-equity-spends-nearly-150-million-to-fuel-2022-races-11667815766",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " $150 million on political races, with the vast majority flowing through super PACs.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Recently, the SEC launched a broad-based crackdown on the private equity industry, and SEC Chair Gary Gensler has positioned himself as an aggressive critic of Wall Street excesses. But cracking down on private equity requires a time-consuming rulemaking process that could ultimately never be completed, due to Congressional pressure and legal challenges.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Expanded enforcement of the pay-to-play rule, however, is a different story ‚Äî and could arguably be even more effective than the suite of new rules proposed by Gensler at reducing the scope of private equity and other alternative investments.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The agency could test the regulation‚Äôs anti-circumvention provisions and begin investigating how and why the Florida state pension fund made their investment decisions. These financial moves don‚Äôt appear to be in the best interest of pensioners ‚Äî our reporting showed in just three years, had the state pension instead been invested in a low-cost index fund, it would now have $10 billion more in its coffers.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "If the SEC actually began issuing subpoenas to governors and other officials with control or influence over public funds requiring them to divulge their calendars, schedules, and text messages ‚Äî and then matched these records up with these politicians‚Äô campaign donations ‚Äî it is probable that the enormous flow of public funds into private equity would slow.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "button",
        "alignment": "center",
